This is an open access article distributed under the Creative Commons Attribution License, which permits unrestricted use,\ndistribution, and reproduction in any medium, provided the original work is properly cited.\n\n\nAbstract\n\nThe most common source of musculoskeletal algia is the myofascial pain syndrome (MPS), its occurrence is related to\nexcessive involuntary muscle contraction and is characterized by hardened regions. Myofascial trigger points (MTP) are\nhypersensitive nodules that refer pain spontaneously or under mechanical stimuli, present in 37 % of men and 65 %\nwomen, and may be classified as: active, latent, satellite, central junction. Assuming this pathological situation affects\nhigh number individuals may cause functional impairment and compromised quality life realized the need enlarge and\nupdate searches about MTP physiology. This literature review was conducted in English, Portuguese, and Spanish\narticles, published since 2009 (trigger points, musculoskeletal pain, MPS) in electronic databases: Bireme, PEDro and\nScielo, and a book 2007. There are four important assumptions about the pathogenesis and pathophysiology of MTP:\nmuscle spindle, the neuropathic process, scar tissue and terminal buttons and dysfunctional energy crisis. Most studies\nhave only two classifications for MTP: active and latent, and few describe in great detail about the possible hypotheses\nof the pathogenesis of these. Recent literature is sparse regarding the physiology and aetiology, however, recent studies\nhave sought to understand the pathophysiology ensure that the hypothesis with the highest validity.\n\nKeywords: Musculoskeletal Pain; Musculoskeletal Physiological; Trigger Points.\n\n\n\n1. Introduction\nThe most common source algia skeletal muscle (muscle, connective tissue and fascia) is myofascial pain syndrome\n(MPS), which is responsible for generating disability in patients who have pain this genre box, but many health\nprofessionals have a recognition flawed on this issue [1], [2], [3].\nThe occurrence of pain is related to excessive involuntary muscle contraction and is characterized by stiff regions, the\npresence of bands of palpable tension, internal to the muscle tissue, and / or associated with fascia and small,\nhypersensitive [4] points, regions hardened [5], [6] and well defined, called myofascial trigger points (MTP). As such,\nthese spontaneously or under mechanical stimulation of the skeletal muscle (muscle, tendon, or fascia) in the presence\nor absence of a adjacent local or pain [7], [8], [9].\nIts existence is related to degenerative, inflammatory, infectious, neoplastic, metabolic, macro or micro trauma of\nvarious structures processes [10], [11] having as injury mechanisms postures, over weight, and physical and emotional\nstress, causing the tensioning on specific muscle groups and / or associates. Affecting mainly the cervical, shoulder\ngirdle, lumbar and temporomandibular joint of individuals in the ost active age groups between 31 and 50 years of age\n[1], [8]. Estimates from a study [12] conducted by Danes found that in 37% of men and 65% women, aged 30-60 years\nhave MTP. In the United States (U.S.), it is believed that the MTP affects 23 million Americans and is therefore\nconsidered a common disorder / neuromuscular dysfunction of motor and sensory origin [10]. Other studies claim that\nthis disorder is prevalent in 20% to 50% of the population of many countries [13].\n
